ttributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents with a 6 hour history of rapid-onset, colicky abdominal pain associated with the passage of loose, bloody stool. She has a history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her regular medications include perindopril, simvastatin, and aspirin. On examination, she is in severe pain with a blood pressure of 140/90mmHg, an irregular pulse rate of 100/min and temperature of 37.4. There is some left sided abdominal tenderness and the rest of the abdomen is soft.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain abdominal X-ray","CT abdomen with IV contrast","Mesenteric angiography","Flexible sigmoidoscopy","Colonoscopy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is \u003Cem\u003Eischaemic colitis\u003C/em\u003E, making a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen with IV contrast\u003C/strong\u003E the investigation of choice. Evidence of colonic wall thickening, pneumatosis and mesenteric stranding should be sought. CT has the added advantage of being able to identify other possible causes of the current problem, should the diagnosis not be ischaemic colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain abdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate in a suspected bowel obstruction, wherein it would demonstrate dilatation of bowel loops and air-fluid levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMesenteric angiography\u003C/strong\u003E would be most appropriate with suspected mesenteric ischaemia. Mesenteric ischaemia refers to an ischaemic process that has affected the vascular supply of the small intestine, whereas the term ischaemic colitis covers a range of situations varying from superficial mucosal involvement to full-thickness transmural necrosis of part or all of the colon. Abdominal pain predominates with mesenteric ischaemia, whilst in ischaemic colitis bloody diarrhoea is often the predominant symptom. Angiography allows direct visualisation of mesenteric vascular occlusion, the extent of the lesion which may be causing it and any possible therapeutic interventions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is useful for the diagnosis of lower gastrointestinal conditions, such as diverticulosis or malignancies, which will demonstrate the macroscopic apperance of the colonic mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColonoscopy \u003C/strong\u003Eare useful for similar reasons to flexible sigmoidoscopy, although extend further through the colon, and should be performed within 48 hours to exclude other types of colitis (tissue biopsies may be required). However, contrast-enhanced CT is a more appropriate in the setting of suspected ischaemic colitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Contrast-enhanced CT scans are the investigation of choice in ischaemic colitis"],"references":["Trotter JM, Hunt L, Peter MB. Ischaemic colitis. Bmj. 2016;355. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28007701/","Hung A, Calderbank T, Samaan MA, Plumb AA, Webster G. Ischaemic colitis: practical challenges and evidence-based recommendations for management. Frontline Gastroenterol. 2019 Dec 13;12(1):44-52. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7802492/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90812"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1244"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90812","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90812"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-11T08:24:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-11T08:25:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1244"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108422"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags",